}}'''John Washington Rogers, Jr.''' (born March 31, 1958) is an [[investment manager]] who founded Ariel Capital Management (now [[Ariel Investments, LLC]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arielinvestments.com/|title=Ariel Investments, LLC|publisher=[[Ariel Investments]]}}</ref> which is the United States' largest minority-run [[mutual fund]] firm,<ref name=FMBCJR8WWWA/> in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forbes.com/investmentnewsletters/2005/12/20/value-servicemaster-investing-in_wt_1220adviserqa_inl.html|title=Outsourcing For Outsized Profits: Whitney Tilson and John Heins, Value Investor Insight|accessdate=2008-12-16|date=2005-12-20|publisher=Forbes.com Inc.|work=[[Forbes]]|author=Tilson, Whitney and John Heins}}</ref>  He is chairman and [[CEO]] of the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usnews.com/usnews/biztech/articles/070726/26housingmarket.htm|title=The Real-Estate Market Still Stinks, but Some Housing Stocks May Be Tempting|accessdate=2008-12-16|date=2007-07-26|publisher=U.S.News & World Report, L.P.|work=[[U.S.News & World Report]]|author=Lim, Paul J.}}</ref>  He served as the Board President of the [[Chicago Park District]] for six years in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usnews.com/usnews/biztech/articles/070513/21best.rogers.htm|title=Best Business Books: John W. Rogers Jr.'s Picks|accessdate=2008-12-16|date=2007-05-13|publisher=U.S.News & World Report, L.P.|work=[[U.S.News & World Report]]|author=Rogers, John W., Jr.}}</ref><ref name=MRN/>  He was [[captain (sports)|captain]] of the 1979<U+2013>80 [[Ivy League]] co-champion [[Princeton Tigers]] men's basketball team.<ref name=FMBCJR8WWWA/>

He has performed other service as board member to several prominent companies, as a leader of several organizations affiliated with his collegiate [[alma mater]], and as a leader in youth education in his native Chicago.  He has been honored with the [[Woodrow Wilson Award]] from Princeton University for the breadth and depth of his service to many organizations.

He was active in the [[Barack Obama presidential campaign, 2008|2008 Barack Obama presidential campaign]] and was a leader of the [[Barack Obama 2009 presidential inauguration|2009 Inauguration]] committee.<ref name=OBBLA/><ref name=Icldt5/>  He has been a regular contributor to ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine for most of the last decade.<ref name=BJWRJ>{{cite web|url=http://search.forbes.com/search/colArchiveSearch?aname=John+W.+Rogers+Jr.&author=john+and+rogers|title=By John W. Rogers Jr.|accessdate=2008-12-19|publisher=Forbes.com LLC|work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>

==Background==
Rogers was raised in the [[Hyde Park, Chicago|Hyde Park]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] of Chicago's [[South Side (Chicago)|South Side]], and graduated from the [[University of Chicago Laboratory Schools]] in 1976.<ref name=MRN/><ref name="news.uchicago.edu">[http://news.uchicago.edu/news.php?asset_id=1651 "http://news.uchicago.edu/news.php?asset_id=1651"]</ref> At the age of 12 his father started giving him [[dividend]]-paying [[stock]]s.<ref name=MRN/>  He went to college at [[Princeton University]], where he used his free time to glean market information at his local stock [[brokerage]] and where he was influenced by [[Burton Malkiel]]'s ''[[A Random Walk Down Wall Street]]''.<ref name=MRN/>

He was a [[college basketball]] teammate of [[Craig Robinson (basketball coach)|Craig Robinson]],<ref name=MRN/> and he served as [[captain (sports)|captain]] of the 1979<U+2013>80 [[Ivy League]] co-champion [[Princeton Tigers]] men's basketball team.<ref name=FMBCJR8WWWA>{{cite web|url=http://www.goprincetontigers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=46548&SPID=4231&DB_OEM_ID=10600&ATCLID=1306494|title=Former Men's Basketball Captain John Rogers <U+2019>80 Wins Woodrow Wilson Award |accessdate=2008-12-16|date=2007-11-08|publisher=Princeton University|author=Qui<U+00F1>ones, Eric}}</ref>  He had a habit of perusing business journals and calling his broker from stadium [[payphone]]s.<ref name=IWAEOTB/>  Rogers credits [[Pete Carril]], his basketball coach, as his greatest college influence because Carril stressed precision and teamwork.<ref name=IWAEOTB/>

Rogers studied [[economics]] at Princeton.<ref name=IWAEOTB/><ref name=WAw/> After graduating in 1980, he worked for [[William Blair & Company]] in Chicago.  A few years later, and with the financial backing of family and friends, he opened his own firm, starting with the Municipal Employees' Annuity & Benefit Fund of Chicago as his first account.<ref name=MRN/>

==Family==
He is the only son of [[Jewel Lafontant]] and John Rogers, Sr.<ref name=MRN/> His mother Jewel was the first African American woman to graduate from the [[University of Chicago Law School]] in 1946.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oberlin.edu/newserv/01jul/mankarious_press_release.html|title=Oberlin College Archives Opens Jewel Lafontant Mankarious Papers|accessdate=2008-12-19|date=2001-07-17|publisher=[[Oberlin College]]}}</ref> She became a prominent [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] lawyer,<ref name=MRN/> and she nominated [[Richard Nixon]], who won the [[List of United States Republican Party presidential tickets|Republican Party Presidential Nomination]], at the [[1960 Republican National Convention]].<ref name=IWAEOTB/> His father was a [[Tuskegee airmen|Tuskegee airman]] pilot with over 100 combat missions of service during [[World War II]] and an eventual Cook County judge for twenty years.<ref name=MRN>{{cite web|url=http://www.smartmoney.com/investing/mutual-funds/mr-rogers-neighborhood-12405/|title=Mr. Rogers' Neighborhood|accessdate=2008-12-16|month=March | year=2002|work=[[SmartMoney]]|author=Young, Lauren}}</ref><ref name=IWAEOTB/> His parents divorced in 1961 and his mother died in 1997.<ref name=MRN/>  Rogers was three years old when his parents divorced.<ref name=IWAEOTB/> He had a daughter, Victoria, with his former wife [[Desir<U+00E9>e Rogers]].<ref name=MRN/>

One of Rogers' great-grandfathers owned the Stratford Hotel in [[Greenwood, Tulsa, Oklahoma]], known as The Black Wall Street.  The hotel was destroyed in the [[Tulsa race riot]].  Rogers helped finance ''Before They Die!'', a documentary detailing some survivor accounts, and made a brief appearance in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackenterprise.com/lifestyle/lifestyle-news/2008/11/21/surviving-destruction-of-%E2%80%98black-wall-street%E2%80%99/|title=Surviving Destruction of <U+2018>Black Wall Street<U+2019>: Black business executives lend time, money to finance New York screening|accessdate=2008-12-18|date=2008-11-21|work=[[Black Enterprise]]|author=Wade, Marcia A.}}</ref>

On December 28, 2002, Rogers married Sharon Fairley who was also a divorcee.<ref name=WCSFJRJ>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/29/style/weddings-celebrations-sharon-fairley-john-rogers-jr.html|title=Weddings/Celebrations; Sharon Fairley, John Rogers Jr.|accessdate=2009-04-27|date=2002-12-29|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>  At the time of her 2002 wedding announcement in ''[[The New York Times]]'', Fairley, who was also a Princeton alumna, was the executive director of consumer marketing and trademark development at [[Pharmacia]].<ref name=WCSFJRJ/>  Fairley currently is an assistant United States Attorney in Chicago.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://paw.princeton.edu/issues/2008/11/05/pages/0482/index.xml|title=Portraits of purpose: Now together for Obama s<U+2019>85, black alumni in Chicago have leading roles in the life of their city|accessdate=2009-04-27|date=2008-11-05|work=[[Princeton Alumni Weekly]]|author=Slevin, Peter}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://74.125.95.132/search?q=cache:wCXSfPPLUe0J:www.usdoj.gov/usao/iln/pr/chicago/2008/pr0521_01.pdf+%22Sharon+Fairley%22&cd=20&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us|title=U.S. Charges 28 Defendants In Alleged Crack Cocaine Conspiracy Involving Gangster Disciples Faction On City's South Side|accessdate=2009-04-27|date=2008-05-21|publisher=[[United States Department of Justice]]}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Rogers has a special overnight delivery subscription with ''[[BusinessWeek]]'' that is delivered via [[Federal Express]] so it is received a day earlier than the regular public.<ref name=MRN/>  He still does not use [[computer]]s or [[e-mail]].<ref name=MRN/>  Rogers is known for wearing gray [[pin stripes|pinstripe]] business [[Suit (clothing)|suit]]s to work.<ref name=MRN/> On the basketball court, he wears black-rimmed [[goggle]]s.<ref name=IWAEOTB/><ref name=THC/>  

Rogers also has a publicly-disclosed set of habits. He has had a diet, which includes on average more than one meal a day from [[McDonald's]] at least since college.<ref name=MRN/>  He only eats simple familiar foods and will return an order because a vegetable touched his meat.<ref name=MRN/>  His family's long-time (over 40 years) housekeeper, Melba Pryer, claims that he buys things such as shaving cream and deodorant in sixes and that he changes his [[toothbrush]] every other week.<ref name=MRN/>  He collects [[teddy bear]]s (especially [[Winnie the Pooh]]).<ref name=MRN/>

Three-on-three basketball has been a continuing part of his life.  As of 2000, he had a team with the second and fourth all-time leading scorers at Princeton, [[Kit Mueller]] (class of 1991) and Robinson (1983) and the schools second leading [[three point shot|three point shooter]] Sean Jackson (1992).  Between 1996 and 2000 his team had won 12 of 17 tournaments that they had entered.<ref name=IWAEOTB>{{cite web|url=http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1020972/index.htm|title=Investor With An Eye On The Ball: The basketball tutorial John Rogers took at Princeton pays dividends every day|accessdate=2008-12-17|date=2000-11-06|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|author=Chen, Albert}}</ref> He scored the game-winning basket of Chicago's three-on-three basketball tournament on a team with [[Arne Duncan]], Robinson, and Kit Mueller.<ref name=MRN/>  Rogers and Robinson were among those invited to practice with [[Michael Jordan]] as he prepared for his comeback.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.princeton.edu/~paw/archive_new/PAW01-02/06-1205/sports.html|title=Playin<U+2019> pickup with His Airness: Alumni helped Michael Jordan back into playing shape|accessdate=2008-12-17|date=2001-12-05|work=[[Princeton Alumni Weekly]]|author=Bernstein, Mark F.}}</ref> He claims to be the first person to have beaten Jordan in a game of one-on-one at one of his fantasy basketball camps.<ref name=JRTS>{{cite web|url=http://www.pbs.org/kcet/tavissmiley/archive/200504/20050415_rogers.html|title=John Rogers|accessdate=2008-12-18|date=2005-04-15|publisher=The Smiley Group, Inc.}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>  Among the witnesses to the victory, which was reported in ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', were [[John Thompson (basketball)|John Thompson, Jr.]], [[Mike Krzyzewski]] and fellow fantasy participant [[Damon Wayans]].<ref name=THC>{{cite web|url=http://www.fannation.com/si_blogs/points_after/posts/2407-the-happiest-camper|title=The Happiest Camper|accessdate=2008-12-18|date=2008-02-26|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|author=Ballard, Chris}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

==Ariel Capital Management/Ariel Investments, LLC==
Rogers was one of the hot stock pickers of the 1980s.<ref name=AFFG/> Rogers uses a [[value investing]] strategy, which has been a problem at times when growth stocks have been the better-performing investment class.<ref name=MRN/><ref name=AFFG>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/archives/1996/b3464105.arc.htm|title=Ariel's Fall From Grace: John Rogers is trying to revive his sagging investment firm|accessdate=2008-12-19|date=1996-02-26|publisher=[[The McGraw-Hill Companies Inc.]]|work=[[BusinessWeek]]|author=Stodghill, Ron}}</ref><ref name=AClmsb>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagobusiness.com/cgi-bin/news.pl?id=23031&seenIt=1|title=Ariel Capital loses more state business|accessdate=2008-12-18|date=2006-11-29|publisher=[[Crain Communications, Inc.]]|work=Chicago Business|author=Strahler, Steven R.}}</ref>  However, his firm and its mutual funds have often been among the industry performance leaders and have on average outperformed the market.<ref name=AFFG/><ref name=AClmsb/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/8c7161ae-aaee-11d9-98d7-00000e2511c8.html|title=Turning on to SRI needn't mean dropping profits|accessdate=2008-12-19|date=2005-04-12|publisher=The Financial Times Ltd|work=[[The Financial Times]]|author=Schurr, Stephen}}</ref>  He eschews investing in new companies or making investments in companies that have no track record.<ref name=JRTS/>  For example, rather than invest in [[AIDS]]-related stocks, he would prefer to invest in hospitals that treat AIDS victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:AJBK&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB7C29C4949238A&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Investing in AIDS-related stock <U+2013> Hunt for cure a plus for several firms|accessdate=2008-12-18|date=1987-03-16|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution]]|author=Geewax, Marilyn}}</ref>  His typical holding period is four or five years rather than the 14-month period of the average mutual fund.<ref name=BHPGB>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2007/06/19/pf/rogers_interview.moneymag/|title=Buy. Hold. Profit. Give Back.: Ariel Capital's John Rogers built an outstanding record investing in a few "great ideas" for the long run. Then he had his own idea: to launch a school to teach inner-city kids about money.|accessdate=2008-12-18|date=2007-07-06|publisher=[[Cable News Network]]|work=[[Money (magazine)|Money]]|author=Zweig, Jason}}</ref> [[Mellody Hobson]] serves as the president of the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=4392711|title=Ariel Investments, LLC|accessdate=2009-01-12|publisher=[[The McGraw-Hill Companies Inc.]]|work=[[BusinessWeek]]}}</ref>

The growth of his company has been steady.  He founded the firm in July 1983 with $10,000, which he turned into $23,170 by the end of February 1984.<ref name=ACML/><ref name=Ciotmtfwp>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CSTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB36D6CEC239D31&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Chicagoan is on the money target firms with potential|accessdate=2008-12-18|date=1987-05-31|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Topolnicki, Denise M.}}</ref> He had financial backing from his mother and other friends and relatives.<ref name=Ciotmtfwp/>  The Ariel fund became public on November 6, 1986.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:WPIW&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB36337CD2A0660&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Information Analysis Inc. Starts Small In Stock Offering|accessdate=2008-12-18|date=1986-11-24|publisher=[[Newsbank]]|work=[[The Washington Post]]|author=Hinden, Stan}}</ref> In November 2000, he had 41 employees.<ref name=IWAEOTB/>  In February 2002, the company had 51 employees and more than 120 institutional clients (including [[United Airlines]], [[ChevronTexaco]], and the [[California State Teachers' Retirement System]]),<ref name=MRN/> which grew to include institutional clients such as [[Wal-Mart]] and [[PepsiCo]] by April 2005.<ref name=JRTS/>  The company has over 100 employees as of 2008.<ref name=ACML>{{cite web|url=http://washington.bizjournals.com/gen/company.html?gcode=6C9D71AB69E14691BD11DD13149CB0DC|title=Ariel Capital Management LLC  |accessdate=2008-12-18|publisher=[[American City Business Journals, Inc.]]}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> In 2008, the company changed its name to [[Ariel Investments, LLC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS141755+15-May-2008+PRN20080515|title=DotCom Marketing Launches New Website for Ariel Investments|accessdate=2009-01-12|date=2008-05-15|publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]]|work=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>

Rogers also has served on the boards of directors of other publicly-traded Chicago-based corporations, including [[Exelon]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.exeloncorp.com/performance/governance/boardofdirectors/rogers.aspx |title=John W. Rogers, Jr., Independent Director |publisher=Exelon Corporation}}</ref> and [[Bally Total Fitness Corporation]], where he was named lead director.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20060111005767/en/Bally-Announces-Appointment-Lead-Director-Establishment-Special
|title=Bally Announces Appointment of Lead Director and Establishment of Special Committee to Lead Strategic Process
|publisher=Bally Total Fitness Corporation
|date=January 11, 2006
|accessdate=April 17, 2011}}</ref> 

Rogers has been a regular contributor to ''[[Forbes]]'' for many years and online archives of his commentaries go back as far as 2001.<ref name=BJWRJ/>  He provides regular personal finance commentaries in a column that has recently been appearing under the title "The Patient Investor".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forbes.com/personalfinance/forbes/2008/1222/108.html|title=It's Time for Equities|accessdate=2008-12-19|date=2008-12-22|publisher=Forbes.com LLC|work=[[Forbes]].com|author=Rogers, John W., Jr.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forbes.com/personalfinance/forbes/2008/1027/210.html|title=It's Time for Equities|accessdate=2008-12-19|date=2008-10-27|publisher=Forbes.com LLC|work=[[Forbes]].com|author=Rogers, John W., Jr.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forbes.com/personalfinance/forbes/2008/0901/114.html|title=Buy Where the Fear Is|accessdate=2008-12-19|date=2008-09-01|publisher=Forbes.com LLC|work=[[Forbes]].com|author=Rogers, John W., Jr.}}</ref>

==Public service==
On February 23, 2008, Rogers became the first African-American winner of a Woodrow Wilson Award from Princeton University for his service to the Princeton alumni community, the Chicago community, the African American community and the financial community.<ref name=FMBCJR8WWWA>{{cite web|url=http://www.goprincetontigers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=46548&SPID=4231&DB_OEM_ID=10600&ATCLID=1306494|title=Former Men's Basketball Captain John Rogers <U+2019>80 Wins Woodrow Wilson Award |accessdate=2008-12-17|date=2007-11-08|publisher=[[Princeton University]]|work=GoPrincetonTigers.com|author=Princeton Athletic Communications}}</ref><ref name=WAw>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivyleaguesports.com/article.asp?intID=6279|title=Wilson Award winner|accessdate=2008-12-17|date=2007-11-09|work=IvyLeague Sports.com|author=Princeton Athletic Communications}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> In 1994, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' featured him as one of its 50 leaders under 40.<ref name=AHoF/>  Rogers is co-chairman of [[Jesse Jackson]]'s annual Wall Street Project minority conference, chairman of the Chicago [[Urban League]], a member of four corporate boards and was a leading campaigner for Princeton basketball legend and [[United States Senator]] [[Bill Bradley]]'s [[United States presidential election, 2000|2000 United States presidential campaign]].<ref name=MRN/>  Three of the boards he serves on are for [[Fortune 500]] companies: [[Aon Corporation]], [[Exelon Corporation]] and [[McDonald's]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arielinvestments.com/content/blogcategory/69/1062/|title=Investment Team|accessdate=2008-12-18|publisher=Ariel Investments, LLC}}</ref>  He is a trustee of the [[University of Chicago]]. He has served numerous civic, educational and arts organizations as a director or trustee, including the [[Rainbow/PUSH Coalition]], the [[Oprah Winfrey]] Foundation and the [[Chicago Symphony Orchestra]].<ref name=WAw/>  At Princeton, he was a trustee of the University from 1990 to 1994 and more recently has served as a member of the Association of Black Princeton Alumni (ABPA) and the Princeton Varsity Club board of directors, as well as the Alumni Schools Committee.<ref name=WAw/>  In the early 1990s, Rogers served as a fundraising leader in [[Project Vote]] [[voter registration]] efforts led by current [[United States President]] [[Barack Obama]].<ref name=WAw/> He has been an advocate for greater diversity in upper-level corporate positions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/4dee88d4-37eb-11dd-aabb-0000779fd2ac.html?nclick_check=1|title=US boardrooms criticised for racial bar|accessdate=2008-12-19|date=2008-06-11|publisher=The Financial Times Ltd|work=[[The Financial Times]]|author=Brewster, Deborah and Chrystia Freeland}}</ref>

Rogers and his company were part of a network of community partners that supported the [[Ariel Community Academy]], which emphasizes financial literacy in its curriculum.<ref name=WAw/>  Rogers donates both time and money to the academy: he has designed curricula and brings students to board meetings.  As a result of his money and time investment 80% of the eighth-grade graduates from the academy are accepted at elite area high schools.<ref name=BHPGB/>  Rogers adopted a class of 40 sixth graders at a cost of $200,000 per year through the "I Have A Dream Foundation".  He expected to pay for college for about 30 of the students.<ref name=AHoF>{{cite web|url=http://cache.zoominfo.com/CachedPage/?archive_id=0&page_id=167036286&page_url=%2f%2fgay.onmoney.com%2fEditorial%2fInvesting%2ffairley%2fmoney_talks_step1.html&page_last_updated=7%2f11%2f2001+6%3a37%3a50+PM&firstName=John&lastName=Rogers|title=Section 1: A Host of Firsts|accessdate=2008-12-18|date=2001-07-11|publisher=Zoom Information Inc.|work=[[OnMoney]]|author=Fairley, Juliette}}</ref> 

He was part of the inner circle of the [[Barack Obama]] presidential campaign.<ref name=OBBLA>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/bwdaily/dnflash/content/nov2008/db2008115_058137.htm|title=Obama's Business Backers Look Ahead: A powerful group of African American executives helped get Obama elected President. Now they hope he can provide solutions to the economic crisis |accessdate=2008-12-19|date=2008-11-06|publisher=[[The McGraw-Hill Companies Inc.]]|work=[[BusinessWeek]]|author=Crockett, Roger O.}}</ref>  He is a long-time Obama associate who serves as the co-chair of Obama's Illinois finance committee and who has been a major fundraiser for Democratic Party candidates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/bacdfa42-38e1-11dd-8aed-0000779fd2ac.html|title=View from the Top|accessdate=2008-12-19|date=2008-06-13|publisher=The Financial Times Ltd|work=[[The Financial Times]]|author=Brewster, Deborah and Chrystia Freeland}}</ref>  He served along with [[William M. Daley|Bill Daley]], [[Pat Ryan (executive)|Pat Ryan]], [[Penny Pritzker]] and [[Julianna Smoot]] on [[Barack Obama 2009 presidential inauguration]] committee.<ref name=Icldt5>{{cite web|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/inauguration-watch/2008/11/presidential_inaugural_committ.html|title=Presidential Inaugural Committee Sets $50,000 Donation Limit|accessdate=2008-12-19|date=2008-11-25|publisher=[[The Washington Post Company]]|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref> In June 2009, Rogers became chairman of the [[University of Chicago Laboratory Schools]]' board.<ref name="news.uchicago.edu"/>

==Legacy==
Since late December 2011, the basketball court in the main competition gym at the [[University of Chicago Laboratory Schools]] has been named after Rogers. Rogers graduated from and played basketball himself at University High School. His name was printed on the floor during Winter Break of the 2011-12 school year, and the court's new title will officially be adopted on February 8, 2012, in a ceremony corresponding with U-High's home game against conference rival [[Northridge Preparatory School|Northridge Prep]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suntimes.com/news/foster/10419192-452/remembering-don.html|title=Remembering Don|accessdate=2012-02-09|date=2012-02-07|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Foster, Stella|quote=The University of Chicago Laboratory School is dedicating the John W. Rogers Jr. Basketball Court at the school on Wednesday, with a reception to follow after the varsity boys game.}}</ref><!--[[WP:AGF]] on details other than the date of the ceremony-->

